	  	  <h1 class="firstHeading">Persia</h1>
	  <div id="bodyContent">
	    <h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia.</h3>
	    <div id="contentSub">(Redirected from <a href="/w/index.php?title=Persian_Empire&amp;redirect=no" title="Persian Empire">Persian Empire</a>)</div>
	    	    	    <!-- start content -->
	    <p><b>Persia</b> is the historical and alternative name for the state of <a href="/wiki/Iran" title="Iran">Iran</a> in the
European languages. The name was used in the West due to the ancient Greek name for Iran, <i>Persis</i>. Persia is used to
describe the nation of Iran, its people, or its ancient empire. Iranians themselves have always, from the earliest times till
today, called their country Iran.</p>
<p>The name <i>Persia</i> comes from a province in the south of Iran, called <i><a href="/wiki/Fars" title="Fars">Fars</a></i> in
the modern <a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian language</a> and <i>Pars</i> in <a href=
"/wiki/Middle_Persian" title="Middle Persian">Middle Persian</a>. <i>Persis</i> is the <a href="/wiki/Greek_language" title=
"Greek language">Hellenized</a> form of Pars, based on which other European nations termed it <i>Persia</i>. This province was
the core of the original Persian Empire. Westerners referred to the state as Persia until <a href="/wiki/March_21" title=
"March 21">March 21</a>, <a href="/wiki/1935" title="1935">1935</a>, when <a href="/wiki/Reza_Shah_Pahlavi" title=
"Reza Shah Pahlavi">Reza Shah Pahlavi</a> formally asked the international community to call the country by its native name,
<a href="/wiki/Iran" title="Iran">Iran</a>, which means the country of <a href="/wiki/Aryan" title="Aryan">Aryans</a>. For the
geography of Fars/Persia, see <a href="/wiki/Geography_of_Iran" title="Geography of Iran">Geography of Iran</a>.</p>
<p>The <a href="/wiki/Persians" title="Persians">Persians</a> are also an ethnic group. Persians are descended from the <a href=
"/wiki/Aryan" title="Aryan">Aryans</a>, an <a href="/wiki/Indo-European" title="Indo-European">Indo-European</a> people that
migrated to the region of Fars from Central Asia c. 1000 BC. Their language is called <a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title=
"Persian language">Persian</a>. According to the <a href="/wiki/2004" title="2004">2004</a> <a href="/wiki/CIA_World_Factbook"
title="CIA World Factbook">CIA World Factbook</a>, 51% of Iran's current population is ethnic Persians. Other estimations, based
on recent data and research, put the figure as high as 70% for ethnic Persians. Persian-speakers are in majority in <a href=
"/wiki/Afghanistan" title="Afghanistan">Afghanistan</a> and <a href="/wiki/Tajikstan" title="Tajikstan">Tajikstan</a>, and form a
large minority in <a href="/wiki/Uzbekistan" title="Uzbekistan">Uzbekistan</a>. Many other ethnic groups are represented in Iran,
including the the linguistically Turkicised Aryan group, the <a href="/wiki/Azerbaijani" title="Azerbaijani">Azerbaijanis</a>,
Iranian <a href="/wiki/Kurd" title="Kurd">Kurds</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Turkmen_people" title="Turkmen people">Turkmens</a>; and
a few <a href="/wiki/Arab" title="Arab">Arabs</a> and other minorities. See <a href="/wiki/Demographics_of_Iran" title=
"Demographics of Iran">Demographics of Iran</a> for more detail.</p>
<p>As an empire and civilization, Persia began in the 7th century BC with the rise of the <a href="/wiki/Achaemenid_dynasty"
title="Achaemenid dynasty">Achaemenid dynasty</a> and has endured to the present day. This civilization was established by ethnic
Persians but very soon spread to other groups by force and by cultural diffusion. Persian culture is one of the cultures with the
longest historical continuity. <a href="/wiki/Persian_language" title="Persian language">Persian language</a> itself is also one
of the earliest documented languages and was one of the first languages to form a standard written version.</p>
<p>A Persian monarch was called a <a href="/wiki/Shah" title="Shah">Shah</a>. See <a href="/wiki/List_of_kings_of_Persia" title=
"List of kings of Persia">List of kings of Persia</a> for a nearly complete list of Persian shahs.</p>
